5 lies I was told about money:

1. Money is the root cause of all evil

We were taught that money is important, but thinking about it is evil.
After all, money was the reason behind fights, wars, and disagreements.

Now I know money is not the cause. 
It is the importance we attach to it in our lives.

2. Be wary of those who are rich

It was always assumed that getting rich was possible only by exploiting others.

Now I know that for every immoral rich person, there are countless more examples of people who treat money, people, and values with respect.

It's just that they are not the ones we hear of or speak of.
Because news covers the abnormal. 

3. Saving money is important

Of course, saving is important. 
But we were never told the complete story. 

That investment is more important.

To make your money beat inflation, we were never taught how to invest.

4. Buying a house is the ultimate financial goal

Paying rent was the classic middle class curse.
Our own home gives us the security and status we ought to have.

Now I know buying a house early in your life is binding and thus, can be a regret-filled decision. 

It most likely doesn't make financial sense (do the math), it also binds you to a size, to a city, and to a locality that you will always find hard to escape thereafter.

5. There are 2 ways to get rich - work in the same place for a really long time, or keep changing jobs every 1-2 years!

Now I know that your salary has nothing to do with your wealth.

It is how much you own of what makes money for you, even when you are sleeping.

The financially wisest people I know kept creating/buying assets - whether their own company, whether stocks, whether IPs, whether a side gig, or investing.

Share this with someone to let them know they’re on the right path, even if it doesn’t seem so.

“I'm 22 and losing interest in everything. What should I do?”

Someone recently asked me this. 
I know a lot of you are also going through this. 

Here is my response:

It’s likely because you have put the pressure of everyone's expectations (including that of yourself) on yourself.
AND have added a deadline to meet that expectation.

It's natural.
We all go through this.
There’s nothing wrong with you. 
Or your life.

It’s just likely that you are living someone else’s life. 
A life that has been decided by you by your parents, by your siblings, by your friends or by the world at large. 
A life that has told you that you are a failure if you don’t have a job by 25, get married and have kids by 30, buy that house, drive that car, have that bank balance. 
And you didn’t question them. 
You just started aiming for that life. 

But it wasn’t your life, was it?
So it is not surprising that you lost interest in living that life. 
Everyday you would get up and drag yourself to show up. 
Because you had to become someone else to live that life. 

You were running away from yourself. 

Run towards yourself. 
No matter how hard it seems.
Because the only way to listen to yourself, is to block the noise from the world. 
And you deserve that silence. 

Define your own success. 
Else, another year will go by and you will feel the same way. 
Not yourself.
